# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vercel-platform
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] The term began being used in the 1990s to describe content delivery networks—these were used to deliver website and video content from servers located near users.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] In the early 2000s, these systems expanded their scope to hosting other applications, leading to early edge computing services.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] These services could do things like find dealers, manage shopping carts, gather real-time data, and place ads.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] The Internet of things (IoT), where devices are connected to the Internet, is often linked with edge computing.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] Edge computing involves running computer programs that deliver quick responses close to where requests are made.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] Karim Arabi, during an IEEE DAC 2014 keynote and later at an MIT MTL Seminar in 2015, described edge computing as computing that occurs outside the cloud, at the network's edge, particularly for applications needing immediate data processing.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] Edge computing is often equated with fog computing, particularly in smaller setups.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] However, in larger deployments, such as smart cities, fog computing serves as a distinct layer between edge computing and cloud computing, with each layer having its own responsibilities.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] "The State of the Edge" report explains that edge computing focuses on servers located close to the end-users.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] Alex Reznik, Chair of the ETSI MEC ISG standards committee, defines 'edge' loosely as anything that's not a traditional data center.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] In cloud gaming, edge nodes, known as "gamelets", are typically within one or two network hops from the client, ensuring quick response times for real-time games.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] Edge computing might use virtualization technology to simplify deploying and managing various applications on edge servers.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] In 2018, the world's data was expected to grow 61 percent to 175 zettabytes by 2025.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] According to research firm Gartner, around 10 percent of enterprise-generated data is created and processed outside a traditional centralized data center or cloud.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] By 2025, the firm predicts that this figure will reach 75 percent.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] The increase in IoT devices at the edge of the network is producing a massive amount of data — storing and using all that data in cloud data centers pushes network bandwidth requirements to the limit.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] Despite the improvements in network technology, data centers cannot guarantee acceptable transfer rates and response times, which often is a critical requirement for many applications.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] Furthermore, devices at the edge constantly consume data coming from the cloud, forcing companies to decentralize data storage and service provisioning, leveraging physical proximity to the end user.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] In a similar way, the aim of edge computing is to move the computation away from data centers towards the edge of the network, exploiting smart objects, mobile phones, or network gateways to perform tasks and provide services on behalf of the cloud.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] By moving services to the edge, it is possible to provide content caching, service delivery, persistent data storage, and IoT management resulting in better response times and transfer rates.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] At the same time, distributing the logic to different network nodes introduces new issues and challenges.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] The distributed nature of this paradigm introduces a shift in security schemes used in cloud computing.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] In edge computing, data may travel between different distributed nodes connected via the internet, and thus requires special encryption mechanisms independent of the cloud.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] This approach minimizes latency, reduces bandwidth consumption, and enhances real-time responsiveness for applications.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] Edge nodes may also be resource-constrained devices, limiting the choice in terms of security methods.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] Moreover, a shift from centralized top-down infrastructure to a decentralized trust model is required.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] On the other hand, by keeping and processing data at the edge, it is possible to increase privacy by minimizing the transmission of sensitive information to the cloud.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] Furthermore, the ownership of collected data shifts from service providers to end-users.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] Scalability in a distributed network must face different issues.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] First, it must take into account the heterogeneity of the devices, having different performance and energy constraints, the highly dynamic condition, and the reliability of the connections compared to more robust infrastructure of cloud data centers.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] Moreover, security requirements may introduce further latency in the communication between nodes, which may slow down the scaling process.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] The state-of-the-art scheduling technique can increase the effective utilization of edge resources and scales the edge server by assigning minimum edge resources to each offloaded task.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] Management of failovers is crucial in order to keep a service alive.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] If a single node goes down and is unreachable, users should still be able to access a service without interruptions.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] Moreover, edge computing systems must provide actions to recover from a failure and alert the user about the incident.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] To this aim, each device must maintain the network topology of the entire distributed system, so that detection of errors and recovery become easily applicable.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] Other factors that may influence this aspect are the connection technologies in use, which may provide different levels of reliability, and the accuracy of the data produced at the edge that could be unreliable due to particular environment conditions.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] As an example, an edge computing device, such as a voice assistant, may continue to provide service to local users even during cloud service or internet outages.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] Edge computing brings analytical computational resources close to the end users and therefore can increase the responsiveness and throughput of applications.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] A well-designed edge platform would significantly outperform a traditional cloud-based system.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] Some applications rely on short response times, making edge computing a significantly more feasible option than cloud computing.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] Examples range from IoT to autonomous driving, anything health or human / public safety relevant, or involving human perception such as facial recognition, which typically takes a human between 370-620 ms to perform.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] Edge computing is more likely to be able to mimic the same perception speed as humans, which is useful in applications such as augmented reality, where the headset should preferably recognize who a person is at the same time as the wearer does.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] Due to the nearness of the analytical resources to the end users, sophisticated analytical tools and artificial intelligence tools can run on the edge of the system.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] This placement at the edge helps to increase operational efficiency and is responsible for many advantages to the system.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] In distributed AI systems on the edge, data compression is increasingly recognized as a foundational design layer to mitigate bandwidth constraints caused by the exchange of large models and high-resolution sensor streams.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] By using servers located on a local edge network to perform those computations, the video files only need to be transmitted in the local network.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] Avoiding transmission over the internet results in significant bandwidth savings and therefore increases efficiency.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] If the recognition is performed locally, it is possible to send the recognized text to the cloud rather than audio recordings, significantly reducing the amount of required bandwidth.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] Edge application services reduce the volumes of data that must be moved, the consequent traffic, and the distance that data must travel.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] That provides lower latency and reduces transmission costs.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] Computation offloading for real-time applications, such as facial recognition algorithms, showed considerable improvements in response times, as demonstrated in early research.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] Further research showed that using resource-rich machines called cloudlets or micro data centers near mobile users, which offer services typically found in the cloud, provided improvements in execution time when some of the tasks are offloaded to the edge node.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] On the other hand, offloading every task may result in a slowdown due to transfer times between device and nodes, so depending on the workload, an optimal configuration can be defined.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] An IoT-based power grid system enables communication of electricity and data to monitor and control the power grid, which makes energy management more efficient.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] Other notable applications include connected cars, self-driving cars, smart cities, Industry 4.0, home automation, missiles,, satellite systems , as well as frameworks such as MediaPipe.
[src:vercel-platform/edge-computing] The growing field of **edge artificial intelligence** (edge AI or edge intelligence, sometimes referred to as "local AI" or "on-device AI") implements artificial intelligence in an edge computing environment, on the device or close to where data is collected.
[src:vercel-platform/jamstack] In JAMstack websites, the application logic typically resides on the client side (for example, an embedded e-commerce checkout service that interacts with pre-rendered static content), without being tightly coupled to a backend server.
[src:vercel-platform/jamstack] JAMstack sites are usually served with a Git-based or headless CMS.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] React documentation mentions Next.js among "Recommended Toolchains" advising it to developers when "building a server-rendered website with Node.js".
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] Where traditional React apps can only render their content in the client-side browser, Next.js extends this functionality to include applications rendered on the server-side.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] The copyright and trademarks for Next.js are owned by Vercel, which also maintains and leads its open-source development.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] Next.js is a React framework that enables several extra features, including server-side rendering and static rendering.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] React is a JavaScript library that is traditionally used to build web applications rendered in the client's browser with JavaScript.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] Developers recognize several problems with this strategy however, such as not catering to users who do not have access to JavaScript or have disabled it, potential security issues, significantly extended page loading times, and harm to the site's overall search engine optimization.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] Frameworks such as Next.js sidestep these problems by allowing some or all of the website to be rendered on the server-side before being sent to the client.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] Next.js is one of the most popular frameworks for React.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] It is one of several recommended "toolchains" available when starting a new app, all of which provide a layer of abstraction to aid in common tasks.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] Next.js requires Node.js and can be initialized using npm.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] Google has contributed to the Next.js project, including 43 pull requests in 2019.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] As of October 2024, the framework is used by many large websites, including Walmart, Apple, Nike, Netflix, TikTok, Uber, Lyft, Starbucks and Spotify.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] In early 2020, Vercel raised $21 million in Series A funding to support improvements to the software.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] The framework's original author, Guillermo Rauch, is currently the CEO of Vercel, and the project's lead maintainer is Tim Neutkens.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] Next.js was first released as an open-source project on GitHub on October 25, 2016.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] It was originally developed based on six principles: out-of-the-box functionality requiring no setup, JavaScript everywhere, all functions are written in JavaScript, automatic code-splitting and server-rendering, configurable data-fetching, anticipating requests, and simplifying deployment.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] Next.js 2.0 was announced in March 2017 including several improvements that made it easier to work with small websites.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] It also increased the build efficiency and improved the scalability of the hot-module replacement feature.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] Version 7.0 was released in September 2018 with improved error handling and support for React's context API for improved dynamic route handling.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] This was also the first version to upgrade to Webpack 4.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] Version 8.0 was released in February 2019 and was the first version to offer serverless deployment of applications, in which the code is split up into lambda functions that are run on demand.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] The version also reduced the time and resources required for static exports and improved prefetch performance.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] Version 9.3, announced in March 2020, included various optimizations and global Sass and CSS module support.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] On July 27, 2020 Next.js version 9.5 was announced, adding new capabilities including incremental static regeneration, rewrites, and redirect support.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] On June 15, 2021 Next.js version 11 was released, introducing among others: Webpack 5 support, preview of real-time collaborative coding functionality "Next.js Live", and experimental function of automatic conversion from Create React App to Next.js compatible form "Create React App Migration".
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] On October 26, 2021, Next.js 12 was released, adding a Rust compiler, making the compilation faster, AVIF support, Edge Functions & Middleware, and Native ESM & URL Imports.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] On October 26, 2022, Vercel released Next.js 13.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] This major release brought about a new routing pattern in beta, with the addition of the App Router that includes support for layouts, React Server Components, streaming, and a new set of data fetching methods.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] Furthermore, Vercel announced a new toolchain for front-end development called Turbo, including Turbopack as a successor to Webpack, Turborepo for incremental build systems.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] In May 2023, Vercel released Next.js 13.4.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] This brought with it the stable version of App Router, which allows developers to use it in production.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] In October 2023, Vercel released Next.js 14, which comes with improved memory management with using edge runtime.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] In October 2024, Vercel released Next.js 15.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] It introduces the Rust-based bundler Turbopack (which is faster than Webpack), support for React 19, and asynchronous request APIs.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] In October 2025, Vercel released Next.js 16.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] Perhaps the most noticeable feature, in terms of open-source, is the Build Adapters API, which allows for easier integration with hosting providers who have custom requirements, despite Vercel supporting self-deployment since 2016 already.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] Next.js supports styling with CSS as well as precompiled Scss and Sass, CSS-in-JS, and styled JSX.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] In addition, it is built with TypeScript support and smart bundling.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] The open-source transpiler SWC is used to transform and compile code into JavaScript usable by a browser.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] Webpack, another open-source tool, is used to bundle the modules afterward, however it is currently being replaced with TurboPack.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] All of these tools are used with npm in a terminal.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] The main feature of Next.js is its use of server-side rendering to reduce the burden on web browsers and provide enhanced security.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] This can be done for any part of the application or the entire system, allowing for content-rich pages to be singled out for server-side rendering.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] It can also be done only for first-time visitors, to reduce the burden on web browsers that have yet to download any of the site's assets.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] The "hot reloading" feature detects changes as they are made and re-renders the appropriate pages so the server avoids the need to be restarted.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] This allows changes made to the application code to be immediately reflected in the web browser, though some browsers will require the page to be refreshed.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] The software uses page-based routing for developer convenience and includes support for dynamic routing.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] Other features include hot-module replacement so that modules can be replaced live, automatic code splitting, which only includes code necessary to load the page, and page prefetching to reduce load time.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] Next.js also supports Incremental Static Regeneration and static site generation - a compiled version of the website is usually built during build time and saved as a .next folder.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] When a user makes a request, the pre-built version which are static HTML pages are cached and sent to them.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] This makes the load time very fast, but it's not suitable for every website, particularly for interactive sites that change often and utilize a lot of user input.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] In November 2025, security researcher Lachlan Davidson reported a vulnerability to the React team that allowed unauthenticated remote code execution through a flaw in the React Server Component deserialization protocol.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] A fix was published to npm on December 3rd and publicly disclosed as CVE-2025-55182 ("React2Shell"), which received a CVSS score of 10.0.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] Next.js versions 15.x and 16.x were affected downstream by this CVE, tracked separately as CVE-2025-66478, as the default App Router configuration was susceptible.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] Amazon threat intelligence teams observed exploitation attempts by multiple Chinese state-nexus threat groups within hours of public disclosure.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] On December 5th, CISA added the vulnerability to its Known Exploited Vulnerabilities (KEV) catalog.
[src:vercel-platform/next-js] On December 6, 2025, Vercel released the npm package fix-react2shell-next for updating to versions with the security fix applied.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] Serverless computing does not eliminate complexity but shifts much of it from the operations team to the development team.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] However, this shift is not absolute, as operations teams continue to manage aspects such as identity and access management (IAM), networking, security policies, and cost optimization.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] Additionally, while breaking down applications into finer-grained components can increase management complexity, the relationship between granularity and management difficulty is not strictly linear.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] There is often an optimal level of modularization where the benefits outweigh the added management overhead.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] According to Yan Cui, serverless techniques should be adopted only when they help to deliver customer value faster.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] And while adopting, organizations should take small steps and de-risk along the way.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] Serverless applications are prone to fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] Monitoring and debugging serverless applications can present unique challenges due to their distributed, event-driven nature and proprietary environments.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] Traditional tools may fall short, making it difficult to track execution flows across services.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] However, modern solutions such as distributed tracing tools (e.g., AWS X-Ray, Datadog), centralized logging, and cloud-agnostic observability platforms are mitigating these challenges.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] Emerging technologies like OpenTelemetry, AI-powered anomaly detection, and serverless-specific frameworks are further improving visibility and root cause analysis.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] While challenges persist, advancements in monitoring and debugging tools are steadily addressing these limitations.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] According to OWASP, serverless applications are vulnerable to variations of traditional attacks, insecure code, and some serverless-specific attacks (like *denial of wallet*).
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] So, the risks have changed and attack prevention requires a shift in mindset.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] Serverless computing is provided as a third-party service.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] Applications and software that run in the serverless environment are by default locked to a specific cloud vendor.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] This issue is exacerbated in serverless computing, as with its increased level of abstraction, public vendors only allow customers to upload code to a FaaS platform without the authority to configure underlying environments.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] More importantly, when considering a more complex workflow that includes backend-as-a-service (BaaS), a BaaS offering can typically only natively trigger a FaaS offering from the same provider.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] This makes the workload migration in serverless computing virtually impossible.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] Therefore, considering how to design and deploy serverless workflows from a multi-cloud perspective could mitigate this.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] Serverless computing may not be ideal for certain high-performance computing (HPC) workloads due to resource limits often imposed by cloud providers, including maximum memory, CPU, and runtime restrictions.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] For workloads requiring sustained or predictable resource usage, bulk-provisioned servers can sometimes be more cost-effective than the pay-per-use model typical of serverless platforms.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] However, serverless computing is increasingly capable of supporting specific HPC workloads, particularly those that are highly parallelizable and event-driven, by leveraging its scalability and elasticity.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] The suitability of serverless computing for HPC continues to evolve with advancements in cloud technologies.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] The *grain of sand* anti-pattern refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] *Lambda pinball* is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are associated with the formation of a distributed monolith.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are often addressed through the application of clear domain boundaries, which distinguish between public and published interfaces.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] Public interfaces are technically accessible interfaces, such as methods, classes, API endpoints, or triggers, but they do not come with formal stability guarantees.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] In contrast, published interfaces involve an explicit stability contract, including formal versioning, thorough documentation, a defined deprecation policy, and often support for backward compatibility.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] Published interfaces may also require maintaining multiple versions simultaneously and adhering to formal deprecation processes when breaking changes are introduced.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] Fragmented chains of function calls are often observed in systems where serverless components (functions) interact with other resources in complex patterns, sometimes described as spaghetti architecture or a distributed monolith.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] In contrast, systems exhibiting clearer boundaries typically organize serverless components into cohesive groups, where internal public interfaces manage inter-component communication, and published interfaces define communication across group boundaries.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] This distinction highlights differences in stability guarantees and maintenance commitments, contributing to reduced dependency complexity.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] Additionally, patterns associated with excessive serverless function chaining are sometimes addressed through architectural strategies that emphasize native service integrations instead of individual functions, a concept referred to as the functionless mindset.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] However, this approach is noted to involve a steeper learning curve, and integration limitations may vary even within the same cloud vendor ecosystem.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] Reporting on serverless databases presents challenges, as retrieving data for a reporting service can either break the bounded contexts, reduce the timeliness of the data, or do both.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] This applies regardless of whether data is pulled directly from databases, retrieved via HTTP, or collected in batches.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] Mark Richards refers to this as the *reach-in reporting* anti-pattern.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] A possible alternative to this approach is for databases to asynchronously push the necessary data to the reporting service instead of the reporting service pulling it.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] While this method requires a separate contract between services and the reporting service and can be complex to implement, it helps preserve bounded contexts while maintaining a high level of data timeliness.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] Adopting DevSecOps practices can help improve the use and security of serverless technologies.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] In serverless applications, the distinction between infrastructure and business logic is often blurred, with applications typically distributed across multiple services.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] To maximize the effectiveness of testing, integration testing is emphasized for serverless applications.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] Additionally, to facilitate debugging and implementation, orchestration is used within the bounded context, while choreography is employed between different bounded contexts.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] Ephemeral resources are typically kept together to maintain high cohesion.
[src:vercel-platform/serverless-computing] However, shared resources with long spin-up times, such as AWS RDS clusters and landing zones, are often managed in separate repositories, deployment pipeline, and stacks.
[src:vercel-platform/vercel] Vercel provides developer tools, frameworks, and cloud infrastructure to build and maintain websites.
[src:vercel-platform/vercel] In September 2025, Vercel raised $300 million in a Series F funding round co-led by Accel and GIC, valuing the company at $9.3 billion.
[src:vercel-platform/vercel] The company maintains a free open-source library for building AI-generated products.
[src:vercel-platform/vercel] Vercel was founded by Guillermo Rauch in 2015 as ZEIT.
[src:vercel-platform/vercel] Rauch had previously created the realtime event-driven communication library Socket.IO and Next.js, the open source framework that Vercel optimized for their platform.
[src:vercel-platform/vercel] ZEIT was rebranded to Vercel in April 2020, although it retained the company's triangular logo.
[src:vercel-platform/vercel] In June 2021, Vercel raised $102 million in a Series C funding round.
[src:vercel-platform/vercel] In 2023, Vercel released an AI web development tool called v0 that creates web applications with natural language prompts; it won a 2025 Webby Award for developer tools.
[src:vercel-platform/vercel] In 2023, Vercel released a software development kit called AI SDK designed to allow developers to build conversational streaming interfaces in JavaScript and TypeScript.
[src:vercel-platform/vercel] In May 2024, Vercel raised $250 million in a funding round which valued the company at $3.25 billion.
[src:vercel-platform/vercel] Later, in September 2025, the company raised a $300 million Series F, receiving a valuation of $9.3 billion.
[src:vercel-platform/vercel] In September 2025, Vercel faced backlash after CEO Guillermo Rauch met with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu amid the Gaza war to discuss artificial intelligence and its application in Israel's economy and defense.
[src:vercel-platform/vercel] In response, several users stated intentions to migrate their applications off of Vercel.
[src:vercel-platform/vercel] In March 2026, Vercel appointed Mitchell Hashimoto, co-founder of HashiCorp and creator of Terraform and Vagrant, to its board of directors.
[src:vercel-platform/vercel] On April 19, 2026, Vercel disclosed a security breach in which certain internal systems were accessed by unauthorized actors.
[src:vercel-platform/vercel] According to the company, the breach originated from the third-party AI tool Context.ai being compromised, which, according to cybersecurity firm Hudson Rock, originated from Lumma Stealer malware infecting an employee's computer after they tried downloading Roblox cheat scripts.
[src:vercel-platform/vercel] The attacker breached a Vercel employee's Google Workspace account, accessing "some Vercel environments and environment variables that were not marked as 'sensitive'".
[src:vercel-platform/vercel] A threat actor claiming to be part of ShinyHunters claimed responsibility and offered stolen data for sale at $2 million on BreachForums, though the post was later deleted and the group reportedly denied involvement.
[src:vercel-platform/vercel] Vercel's architecture is built around composable architecture, and deployments are handled through Git repositories, the Vercel CLI, or the Vercel REST API.
[src:vercel-platform/vercel] Vercel is a member of the MACH Alliance.
[src:vercel-platform/vercel] Deployments through Vercel are handled through Git repositories, with support for GitHub, GitLab, and Bitbucket repositories.
[src:vercel-platform/vercel] Deployments are automatically given a subdomain under the `vercel.app` domain, although Vercel offers support for custom domains for deployments.
[src:vercel-platform/vercel] Vercel's infrastructure uses Amazon Web Services.
[src:vercel-platform/vercel] In 2025, Vercel introduced a web application infrastructure model called Fluid that enables an instance in a local region to handle multiple requests concurrently, similar to a traditional server, while also maintaining the elasticity of serverless systems.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] A **web hosting service** is a type of Internet hosting service that hosts websites for clients, i.e. it offers the facilities required for them to create and maintain a site and makes it accessible on the World Wide Web.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Companies providing web hosting services are sometimes called *web hosts*.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Until 1991, the Internet was restricted to use only "... for research and education in the sciences and engineering ..." and was used for email, telnet, FTP and USENET traffic—but only a tiny number of web pages.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] The World Wide Web protocols had only just been written, and there wouldn't be a graphical web browser for Mac or Windows computers until the end of 1993.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Even after there was some opening up of Internet access, the situation was confused until 1995.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] To host a website on the internet, an individual or company would need their own computer or server.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] As not all companies had the budget or expertise to do this, web hosting services began to offer to host users' websites on their own servers, without the client needing to own the necessary infrastructure required to operate the website.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] The owners of the websites, also called webmasters, would be able to create a website that would be hosted on the web hosting service's server and published to the web by the web hosting service.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] As the number of users on the World Wide Web grew, the pressure for companies, both large and small, to have an online presence grew.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] By 1995, companies such as GeoCities, Angelfire and Tripod were offering free hosting.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Static web page files can be uploaded via File Transfer Protocol (FTP) or a web interface, or automatically deployed from a repository using a Continuous Integration tool.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] For example, static page hosting services such as GitHub Pages or Cloudflare Pages often build directly from source control systems such as Git.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] The files are usually delivered to the Web "as is", or with minimal processing, e.g. by using a static site generator such as 11ty.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Many Internet service providers (ISPs) offer this service free to subscribers.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Individuals and organizations may also obtain web page hosting from alternative service providers.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Free web hosting service is offered by different companies with limited services, sometimes supported by advertisements, and often limited when compared to paid hosting.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Single page hosting is generally sufficient for personal web pages.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Personal website hosting is typically free, advertisement-sponsored, or inexpensive.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Business website hosting often has a higher expense depending upon the size and type of the site.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Peer-to-peer web hosting is using peer-to-peer networking to distribute access to webpages.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] This is differentiated from the client–server model which involves the distribution of web data between dedicated web servers and user-end client computers.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Peer-to-peer web hosting may also take the form of P2P web caches and content delivery networks.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] A complex site calls for a more comprehensive package that provides database support and application development platforms (e.g.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] ASP.NET, ColdFusion, Java EE, Perl/Plack, PHP or Ruby on Rails).
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] These facilities allow customers to write or install scripts for applications like forums and content management.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Web hosting packages often include a web content management system, so the end-user does not have to worry about the more technical aspects.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) is used for websites that wish to encrypt the transmitted data.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Internet hosting services can run web servers.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] The scope of web hosting services varies greatly.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] One's website is placed on the same server as many other sites, ranging from a few sites to hundreds of websites.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] The features available with this type of service can be quite basic and not flexible in terms of software and updates.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] often sell shared web hosting and web companies often have reseller accounts to provide hosting for clients.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Allows clients to become web hosts themselves.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Resellers could function, for individual domains, under any combination of these listed types of hosting, depending on who they are affiliated with as a reseller.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Resellers' accounts may vary tremendously in size: they may have their own virtual dedicated server to a colocated server.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Many resellers provide a nearly identical service to their provider's shared hosting plan and provide the technical support themselves.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] (VPS), divides server resources into virtual servers, where resources can be allocated in a way that does not directly reflect the underlying hardware.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] VPS will often be allocated resources based on a one server to many VPSs relationship, however virtualisation may be done for a number of reasons, including the ability to move a VPS container between servers.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Customers are sometimes responsible for patching and maintaining the server (unmanaged server) or the VPS provider may provide server admin tasks for the customer (managed server).
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] for Linux/administrator access for Windows); however, the user typically does not own the server.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] One type of dedicated hosting is self-managed or unmanaged.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] This is usually the least expensive for dedicated plans.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] The user has full administrative access to the server, which means the client is responsible for the security and maintenance of their own dedicated server.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] The user gets their own web server but is not allowed full control over it (user is denied root access for Linux/administrator access for Windows); however, they are allowed to manage their data via FTP or other remote management tools.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] The user is disallowed full control so that the provider can guarantee quality of service by not allowing the user to modify the server or potentially create configuration problems.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] The user typically does not own the server.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Similar to the dedicated web hosting service, but the user owns the colo server; the hosting company provides physical space that the server takes up and takes care of the server.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] This is the most powerful and expensive type of web hosting service.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] In most cases, the colocation provider may provide little to no support directly for their client's machine, providing only the electrical, Internet access, and storage facilities for the server.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] In most cases for colo, the client would have their own administrator visit the data center on site to do any hardware upgrades or changes.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] enclosures and standard system configurations.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Hosting based on clustered load-balanced servers.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] A cloud hosted website may be more reliable than alternatives since other computers in the cloud can compensate when a single piece of hardware goes down.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Also, local power disruptions or even natural disasters are less problematic for cloud hosted sites, as cloud hosting is decentralized.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Cloud hosting also allows providers to charge users only for resources consumed by the user, rather than a flat fee for the amount the user expects they will use, or a fixed cost upfront hardware investment.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Cloud hosting users can request additional resources on-demand such as only during periods of peak traffic, while offloading IT management to the cloud hosting service.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Having multiple servers hosting the same content for better resource utilization.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Clustered servers are a perfect solution for high-availability dedicated hosting, or creating a scalable web hosting solution.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] A cluster may separate web serving from database hosting capability.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] (Usually web hosts use clustered hosting for their shared hosting plans, as there are multiple benefits to the mass managing of clients).
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] This form of distributed hosting is when a server cluster acts like a grid and is composed of multiple nodes.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] These can be purpose-built machines or more commonly old PCs.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] The host may also provide an interface or control panel for managing the web server and installing scripts, as well as other modules and service applications like e-mail.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] A web server that does not use a control panel for managing the hosting account, is often referred to as a "headless" server.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Some hosts specialize in certain software or services (e.g. e-commerce, blogs, etc.).
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] The availability of a website is measured by the percentage of a year in which the website is publicly accessible and reachable via the Internet.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] This is different from measuring the uptime of a system.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Uptime refers to the system itself being online.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Uptime does not take into account being able to reach it as in the event of a network outage.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] A hosting provider's Service Level Agreement (SLA) may include a certain amount of scheduled downtime per year in order to perform maintenance on the systems.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] This scheduled downtime is often excluded from the SLA timeframe, and needs to be subtracted from the Total Time when availability is calculated.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Depending on the wording of an SLA, if the availability of a system drops below that in the signed SLA, a hosting provider often will provide a partial refund for time lost.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] How downtime is determined changes from provider to provider, therefore reading the SLA is imperative.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Not all providers release uptime statistics.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Because web hosting services host websites belonging to their customers, online security is an important concern.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] When a customer agrees to use a web hosting service, they are relinquishing control of the security of their site to the company that is hosting the site.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] The level of security that a web hosting service offers is extremely important to a prospective customer and can be a major factor when considering which provider a customer may choose.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] Web hosting servers can be attacked by malicious users in different ways, including uploading malware or malicious code onto a hosted website.
[src:vercel-platform/web-hosting-service] These attacks may be done for different reasons, including stealing credit card data, launching a Distributed Denial of Service Attack (DDoS) or spamming.
